notes:
OrigID: H. sachalinensis by Suvdtsetseg Chuluunbat.

H. tessellatus and H. sachalinensis could be synonyms. A. sachalinensis needs to be redescribed. Schmid didn`t see the real specimen but copied Martynov`s figure. -Oliver Flint

"This is Halesus tessellatus (Rambur, 1842). The illustrations provided by Martynov (1914) in his original description for H. sachalinensis show a much more prominent and acute inner tooth of each inferior appendage, even more prominent than shown by Nimmo, Arefina, & Levanidova (in "Key to the Insects of the Russian Far East, Volume 5, Trichoptera and Lepidoptera," edited by P.A. Lera, 1997), and certainly larger than the hint of a tooth illustrated for H. tessallatus by Malicky (European Atlas, 2004). The preanal appendages and the "intermediate appendages" of the 2 species also are rather different. The question whether these differences are sufficiently significant to maintain the 2 species as distinct is one that would have to be answered with COI sequences from Sakhalin Island (the type locality of H. sachalinensis) and other parts of Russia."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.
